, New York]]\n|[[Rybnitsa]], [[Moldova]]/[[Transnistria]]\n|-\n|'''[[Vien (Hasidic community)|Vien]]'''\n|\n|[[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]], [[Brooklyn]]\n|[[Vienna]], [[Austria]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n* Rabinowicz, Tzvi M. ''The Encyclopedia of Hasidism'' {{ISBN|1-56821-123-6}} Jason Aronson, Inc., 1996.\n* Alfasi, Yitschak. ''\u05d4\u05d7\u05e1\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05de\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8 \u05dc\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8''    ''Hachasidut miDor leDor''   (2 vols)\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hasidic dynasties}}\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hasidic Dynasties}}\n[[Category:Hasidic dynasties| ]]\n[[Category:Jewish families]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Main|Hasidic Judaism}}\nA '''Hasidic dynasty''' is a [[dynasty]] led by [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] [[Jews|Jewish]] spiritual leaders known as [[rebbe]]s,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | year =2012| title =Hasidism| encyclopedia =[[World Book]]|volume=9|page=82}}</ref> and usually has some or all of the following characteristics:\n* Each leader of the dynasty is often known as an ''ADMOR''<ref>{{cite news|title=Hasidic leader Yaakov Friedman, the Admor of Sadigura, dies at 84|first= Yair|last=Ettinger|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/hasidic-leader-yaakov-friedman-the-admor-of-sadigura-dies-at-84-1.491294|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=Jan 1, 2013|accessdate=Oct 14, 2013}}</ref> (abbreviation for '' '''AD'''oneinu '''MO'''reinu '''R'''abeinu'' - \"our master, our teacher and our rabbi\") or simply as ''[[Rebbe]]'' (or \"the Rebbe\"), and at times called the \"Rav\" (\"rabbi\"), and sometimes referred to in English as a \"Grand Rabbi\";\n* The dynasty continues beyond the initial leader's lifetime by succession (usually by a family descendant);\n* The dynasty is usually named after a key town in Eastern Europe where the founder may have been born or lived, or where the group began to grow and flourish;\n* The dynasty has (or once had) followers who, through time, continue following successive leaders (rebbes) or may even continue as a group without a leader by following the precepts of a deceased leader.\n\nA '''Hasidic group''' has the following characteristics:\n* It was founded by a leader who did not appoint or leave a successor;\n* It may be named after a key town in Eastern Europe where the founder may have been born or lived, or where the group began to grow and flourish, or it may be named after the founder himself;\n* It has followers who continue as a group under the direction of rabbis who expound and interpret the precepts of the deceased founder.\n\n==Dynasties with larger following==\nHasidic dynasties (arranged alphabetically) with a large following include:\n\n{|class=\"toccolours\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Current (or last) Rebbe\n!Founder\n!Headquartered In\n!City/Town of Origin\n|-\n|'''[[Belz (Hasidic dynasty)|Belz]]'''\n|[[Yissachar Dov Rokeach (fifth Belzer rebbe)|Yissachar Dov Rokeach]]\n|[[Sholom Rokeach]] (1781\u20131855)\n|[[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]\n|[[Belz]], Galicia, Austria-Hungary / Poland (now in [[Ukraine]])\n|-\n|'''[[Bobov (Hasidic dynasty)|Bobov]]'''<br>\n([[Bobov-45]])\n|[[Ben Zion Aryeh Leibish Halberstam]]<br>\n[[Mordechai Dovid Unger]] (b.1954)\n|[[Shlomo Halberstam (first Bobover rebbe)|Shlomo Halberstam of Bobov]] (1847\u20131905)\n|[[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]], [[Brooklyn]]\n|[[Bobowa]] and [[Nowy S\u0105cz|Sanz]], Galicia, Austria-Hungary (now in Poland)\n|-\n|'''[[Chabad|Chabad Lubavitch]]'''\n|[[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]] (1902-1994)\n|[[Schneur Zalman of Liadi]] (1745\u20131812)\n|[[Crown Heights, Brooklyn]]\n|[[Lyubavichi, Rudnyansky District, Smolensk Oblast|Lyubavichi]], Russia \n|-\n|'''[[Ger (Hasidic dynasty)|Ger]]'''\n|[[Yaakov Aryeh Alter]] (b. 1939)\n|[[Yitzchak Meir Alter]] (1799\u20131866)\n|Jerusalem, Israel\n|[[G\u00f3ra Kalwaria]], Russian Empire (now in Poland)\n|-\n|'''[[Karlin-Stolin (Hasidic dynasty)|Karlin-Stolin]]'''\n|